keyRaces.name: Arizona
keyRaces.description: Donald Trump won Arizona in 2016 by nearly 4 percentage points, but lost the state to Joe Biden in 2020 by less than half a percentage point. Polls this year have found Trump and Kamala Harris locked in a statistical tie.

keyRaces.name: Georgia
keyRaces.description: Donald Trump won Georgia in 2016 by about 5 percentage points, but lost there to Joe Biden in 2020 by less than 12,000 votes. The race this year is a toss-up, with Trump and Harris locked in a statistical tie in polls.

keyRaces.name: Michigan
keyRaces.description: Donald Trump won Michigan in 2016, surprising Democrats in a state Republicans hadn’t won since 1988. Joe Biden won there in 2020 – besting Trump by 3 percentage points. With Kamala Harris and Trump in a statistical tie, it is a “toss-up” headed into Election Day.

keyRaces.name: Nebraska District 2
keyRaces.description: Nebraska awards one Electoral College vote each to its two congressional districts, and the 2nd District has split from the rest of the reliably conservative state. Donald Trump won the district in 2016, but lost it to Joe Biden in 2020. The district is leaning in polls toward the Democrat Kamala Harris this year.

keyRaces.name: Nevada
keyRaces.description: Democrats won Nevada in the past two presidential elections — but polling and voting trends in the state have made it an appealing target for Donald Trump in a bid to flip states in his direction. Kamala Harris and Trump are locked in a tie and the state is considered a “toss-up.”

keyRaces.name: North Carolina
keyRaces.description: North Carolina hasn’t voted for a Democrat for president since 2008, but Kamala Harris’ campaign has targeted it as a state she can win, buoyed by its large Black population. Donald Trump won there in 2016 by 3 percentage points and in 2020 by 1 percentage point.

keyRaces.name: Wisconsin
keyRaces.description: Wisconsin is a “toss-up” battleground state that has swung between Democrats and Republicans. Donald Trump won there in 2016 by less than 1 percentage point. Joe Biden won there in 2020, also by less than 1 percentage point.

keyRaces.name: Pennsylvania
keyRaces.description: Pennsylvania is emerging as the most critical battleground state in the 2024 election. Donald Trump won the state by less than 1 percentage point in 2016 and lost it by about 1 percentage point in 2020. Kamala Harris has remained competitive there, and the state is classified as a “toss-up.”

The expected vote is the total number of votes that are expected in a given race once all votes are counted. This number is an estimate and is based on several different factors, including information on the number of votes cast early as well as information provided to our vote reporters on Election Day from county election officials. The figure can change as NBC News gathers new information.

**Source**: [National Election Pool (NEP)](https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2024-elections/how-election-data-is-collected)

states.description: Donald Trump won Arizona in 2016 by nearly 4 percentage points, but lost the state to Joe Biden in 2020 by less than half a percentage point. Polls this year have found Trump and Kamala Harris locked in a statistical tie.

Donald Trump won Georgia in 2016 by about 5 percentage points, but lost there to Joe Biden in 2020 by less than 12,000 votes. The race this year is a toss-up, with Trump and Harris locked in a statistical tie in polls.

Donald Trump won Michigan in 2016, surprising Democrats in a state Republicans hadn’t won since 1988. Joe Biden won there in 2020 – besting Trump by 3 percentage points. With Kamala Harris and Trump in a statistical tie, it is a “toss-up” headed into Election Day.

Nebraska awards one Electoral College vote each to its two congressional districts, and the 2nd District has split from the rest of the reliably conservative state. Donald Trump won the district in 2016, but lost it to Joe Biden in 2020. The district is leaning in polls toward the Democrat Kamala Harris this year.

Democrats won Nevada in the past two presidential elections — but polling and voting trends in the state have made it an appealing target for Donald Trump in a bid to flip states in his direction. Kamala Harris and Trump are locked in a tie and the state is considered a “toss-up.”

North Carolina hasn’t voted for a Democrat for president since 2008, but Kamala Harris’ campaign has targeted it as a state she can win, buoyed by its large Black population. Donald Trump won there in 2016 by 3 percentage points and in 2020 by 1 percentage point.

Wisconsin is a “toss-up” battleground state that has swung between Democrats and Republicans. Donald Trump won there in 2016 by less than 1 percentage point. Joe Biden won there in 2020, also by less than 1 percentage point.

Pennsylvania is emerging as the most critical battleground state in the 2024 election. Donald Trump won the state by less than 1 percentage point in 2016 and lost it by about 1 percentage point in 2020. Kamala Harris has remained competitive there, and the state is classified as a “toss-up.”

page.description: Voters in all 50 states and the District of Columbia will cast ballots in the presidential contest between Democrat Kamala Harris and Republican Donald Trump. Presidents are elected using the Electoral College and a candidate needs at least 270 Electoral College votes to win. Most states allocate all of their Electoral College votes to the winner of the state’s popular vote. Nebraska and Maine both divide their votes.

markupAndEmbeds.html: In a radio interview today, Harris touted her opportunity agenda, particularly as it relates to Black men, which she said reflects her longstanding commitment to addressing economic disparities.

“This is not something I just figured out, that we still have a lot to do to recognize the disparities in what Black men receive and what they are due in terms of access to opportunity,” she told "The Big Tigger Morning Show" based in Atlanta.
Harris said that agenda includes putting more capital into small businesses and a $20,000 forgivable loan for startups that need financial help.

She also discussed the significance of going to her alma mater, Howard University, tonight for her watch party with the host, Darian “Big Tigger” Morgan. If elected, Harris would be the first president to have graduated from a historically Black college or university, which she said was not lost on her.
“The first office I ever ran for was freshman class representative at Howard University,” she said, adding that it would be a full-circle moment for her if she wins.

Harris said she and Trump, whom she did not mention by name, had “two very different visions of the future of our nation,” repeating her common attacks on him claiming he's full of vengeance, grievances and “all about himself.” She a;sp said she doesn’t pay attention to “misinformation” about her and “vitriol” directed at her.
Harris also said she’s honored that artists like rapper Plies and will.i.am have made songs about her.
Her closing message to undecided voters is that she is focused on addressing the high cost of housing and child care while her opponent was focused on his own grievances, she said.

markupAndEmbeds.html: Music greeted voters who turned out early this morning to cast their ballots at the Pittsburgh Mennonite Church in the borough of Swissvale, where a DJ was set up outside the church’s entrance.
Turnout so far was "as good, if not better" than usual, Seth Bush, a member of the Swissvale Democratic Committee, said in between greeting voters and answering questions.
Voter Sabrina Promwell, 54, a Swissvale resident, said she’s been voting since she turned 18.
“My father fought for this country, so I like to hear my voice and I’m out here so my voice can be heard,” she said, declining to reveal her choice.
Promwell encouraged others to get out and do the same. “If you’re not out here, get out here and do the right thing, vote, or you have no voice,” she said.
Bush, 34, said turnout has been good for general elections in Swissvale over the past few years.
“I feel proud of my neighbors,” he said. “Voting is a vital part of the process. It’s something that everybody … can do and should do.”

I have traveled across the country to report on the mass shooting at Tops Friendly Markets in Buffalo, New York; the arrest of Idaho murder suspect Bryan Kohberger; the 2022 floods in eastern Kentucky; the shooting of Jayland Walker in Akron, Ohio; the mass shooting in Lewiston, Maine; and many more. markupAndEmbeds.html: The chair of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, which works to elect Democrats to the House, sounded a note of confidence this morning that her party would win the House majority, citing its candidates and resources, and predicting that voters “are tired of the chaos and dysfunction and extremism from Republicans.”

“We’re in a really strong position ... Just incredible energy, enthusiasm on the ground," Chair Rep. Suzan DelBene, D-Wash., told NBC News by phone from Washington. "So we’re still going to work hard all through today to get out every vote. I do think there are a lot of crossover Republicans that we’re going to see in districts across the country that may not be in a lot of people’s numbers.”
But DelBene said she isn't holding her breath for a result today, a sign that Democrats expect another close battle that could come down to a few seats.

“I think it was eight days in 2022 before we knew who had the majority,” she said. “I definitely think that we might have to wait because some of these races are going to be really close and might take a few days to call — especially for folks looking at mail-in ballots or other things that might take a little while. So we may not know tonight.”

The DCCC chair wouldn’t make predictions on the size of the majority. Asked if she worries that a Republican-controlled House wouldn’t certify a potential Harris victory Jan. 6, DelBene said that if Democrats win the House, the GOP won’t have the power to prevent it.
“Hakeem Jeffries will be speaker when we certify the election,” she said.
DelBene also wouldn’t say if she will continue as DCCC chair for the 2026 cycle. “I haven’t even thought about it for a second,” she responded. “I have one focus, which is to win this election.”

markupAndEmbeds.html: Florida’s Equal Ground, which says it works to mobilize Black voters to take part in elections, tells NBC News the nonprofit has deployed pastors to polls across the state ahead of Election Day, with a focus on Lee, Polk, Hillsborough and Orange counties.
It’s part of its Pastors at the Polls program, and it had pastors in these counties for early voting, as well.
It says the pastors are trained in de-escalation in case of heightened tension at the polls in precincts where there’s a fear of voter intimidation.

markupAndEmbeds.html: Trump Media, the parent company of the former president's Truth Social platform, jumped more than 15% in early trading as voters head to the polls.

The stock, which trades as the ticker symbol DJT, is notoriously volatile and is broadly considered a meme stock. Just last week, the shares fell from an intraday high of more than $54 last Tuesday before falling to about $30 Friday.

The fundamentals of the business aren't particularly strong. In August, it posted a $16 million quarterly loss and revenue of less than $1 million. Yet its market value was nearly $8 billion as of this morning. The New York Times, by comparison, has a market capitalization of about $8.7 billion.
Trump owns a 57% stake in Trump Media, which translates to about $4.5 billion as of this morning.

markupAndEmbeds.html: Voters from southeast Texas north to Illinois will likely have to contend with rounds of heavy rain and possible flooding as they head to the polls today.

A line of strong thunderstorms is bringing morning rain and storms to a swath of the country from the Gulf to the Midwest, affecting cities such as Chicago, St. Louis, Little Rock, Shreveport and Houston. The storms are expected to clear out by midday.

Some snow and gusty winds are expected in the Rockies, with rain and snow showers in the forecast for parts of the Pacific Northwest. In the Southwest, Arizona and Nevada will be mostly sunny with cooler temperatures. And on the East Coast, it will mostly be dry skies and record warm temperatures.
